    "active_paradigms": [
      {
        "idea": "Generalized Richards sigmoid with power-law time and concentration coupling",
        "description": "Replace the symmetric logistic with a Richards/generalized logistic: y = c0 / (1 + c4*exp(-rate*(lt - halftime)))^(1/c8) + c4_baseline. The asymmetry parameter 1/c8 allows the curve to be skewed left or right, which is physically meaningful for nucleation-limited aggregation (fast nucleation = left-skewed, slow nucleation = right-skewed). Keep arcsinh time transformation for stability. Simplify halftime to pure power-law c3*x1^c6 and rate to c1*x1^c5 (drop the log-quadratic terms that may destabilize fitting on small datasets). Initialize c8=1 to recover standard logistic. This reduces constants from 9 to 8 while adding more expressive shape flexibility. The key insight is that protein aggregation kinetics are often asymmetric due to the nucleation mechanism.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Fit quality on datasets with asymmetric sigmoidal shapes; robustness on small datasets by reducing parameter count",
        "cautions": "The power (1/c8) can cause numerical issues if c8 near 0; add a small offset or initialize c8=1.0 and bound away from 0. Ensure the base of the power is always positive by using absolute value or restructuring.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.generalized_logistic"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Double-sigmoid (two-phase) aggregation model with shared x1 coupling",
        "description": "Some protein aggregation datasets show biphasic kinetics (primary + secondary nucleation). Model as sum of two logistic terms: y = c0/(1+exp(-c1*(lt-c2))) + c3/(1+exp(-c4*(lt-c5))) + c6, where rates and halftimes each have simple linear x1 dependence folded in. Keep arcsinh time transformation. This captures datasets where a single sigmoid fits poorly because there are two distinct aggregation phases. Initialize second sigmoid with smaller amplitude (c3 init=0.2) and later halftime. Total 7 constants. The structural principle is that secondary nucleation (surface-catalyzed) creates a second kinetic phase distinct from primary nucleation.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Datasets with biphasic or non-standard sigmoidal shapes that the single sigmoid underfits",
        "cautions": "Two sigmoids can be hard to distinguish during fitting (identifiability). Keep second amplitude small at initialization. The two phases may collapse to one on simple datasets, which is fine. Ensure x1 coupling doesn't over-parameterize.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.double_sigmoid"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Nucleation-elongation kinetic model: Finke-Watzky two-step mechanism",
        "description": "The Finke-Watzky (FW) model is the standard mechanistic model for protein aggregation: dA/dt = -k1*A - k2*A*B, giving an integrated sigmoidal form y = (k1/k2) / (1 + (k1/(k2*A0))*exp((k1+k2*A0)*t)) where A0 is initial monomer. This maps to: y = c0 / (1 + c1*exp(-c2*(x0 - c3))) + c4, but with x1 coupling via c2 = c5*x1^c6 (rate scales with concentration) and c3 = c7/x1^c8 (halftime inversely scales). The key structural difference from current: halftime uses INVERSE power law (1/x1^c8) which is physically correct - higher concentration means faster aggregation (shorter halftime). Keep arcsinh time transform for numerical stability. 9 constants total.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Physical correctness of concentration dependence; better extrapolation; improved fit on concentration-series datasets",
        "cautions": "Inverse power law c7/x1^c8 requires x1>0 (guaranteed by data structure). Initialize c8=1 for linear inverse scaling. The arcsinh transform changes the effective time variable so halftime meaning changes - may need different initialization.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.finke_watzky_mechanism"
      }
    ],
